\cf0 \ul Accuracy of H3\ulnone \
I have verified that both methods accurately compute H3 through few of tests. The tests are: \
1) Comparing to an exact solution for H3 and H2 in the case of two modes of arbitrary values. \
2) Comparing the two computations of H3 for an arbitrary number of modes with random values.\
Some notes are:\
\'95 If upsampling is removed from the FFT method, the results are no longer accurate, as would be expected.\
\'95 I have found that if I change the upsampling to 3/2 and zero out the largest mode, then the FFT results are still accurate. If I keep the largest mode, though, then 3/2 upsampling does not give accurate results, but 3/2 + 1 upsampling does give accurate results. However, none of this really matters because upsampling by a factor of 2 is probably just as efficient as 3/2 (almost certainly more efficient than 3/2 + 1) and in that case I do not have to worry about killing the largest mode.\
\
\ul Speed of H3\ulnone \
After much testing and improvement of the algorithms, these two methods are competitive for moderate Lambda (16 or 32) and the FFT method is superior for Lambda = 64 and great. Some results are:\
\'95 For Lambda = 16, REC is about 3 times faster.\
\'95 For Lambda = 32, REC is about 1.5 times faster.\
\'95 For Lambda = 64, FFT is about 1.3 times faster.\
\'95 The break even point is about Lambda = 48 (corresponding to an FFT of size 96).\
\'95 See the saved plots in folder H3SpeedTest from May 4-5, 2020.\
\
