\cf0 \ul FFT Notes\ulnone \
I discovered a number of things about the FFT. The lessons are:\
\'95 You need to make a plan! It is easy to do and it massively improves the efficiency. Speed-ups of about 5 are typical, sometimes the speed-up is up to 10.\
\
\'95 The convention for using the inverse real FFT is:\
irfft(uh_0, uh_1, \'85, uh_\{N-1\}, 2*uh_N)\
- Notice the largest mode u_N is multiplied by 2.\
- Additionally, the largest mode uh_N should be real for things to be interpreted in a reasonable way. The largest mode is allowed to be complex in the routine irfft, but its imaginary part will make no difference in the output physical signal u. This behavior makes sense with a bit of analysis. The imaginary part of the larges mode corresponds to sin of the Nyquist frequency, which aliases to zero and hence cannot be seen by the physical grid. It also makes sense through a basic count of the degrees of freedom, noting that uh_0 must also be real, since it is the mean of real data.\
- The size of the irfft output is allowed to be either 2*N or 2*N+1, see reference: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://juliamath.github.io/AbstractFFTs.jl/stable/api/"}}{\fldrslt https://juliamath.github.io/AbstractFFTs.jl/stable/api/}}. For efficiency, though, you really only want 2*N, which I have verified through tests.\
- Of course, one can pad with zeros in order to upsample. Once you pad with zeros, there is no need to worry about the idiosyncrasies of the largest mode, since it is zero. I have found it is best to pad with N zeros, i.e. double the number of modes not counting uh_0. One could also apply the 3/2 rule, but I see no advantage to it (see notes above on H3).\
- By default, the physical interval is [0, 2*pi). To use the symmetric interval [-pi, pi) one can negate all of the odd modes.\
- The routine irfft within FFT destroys its input, uhat!!! One needs to keep this in mind to keep from getting ambushed with weird bugs. The routine rfft, however, does not destroy its input.\
\
\'95 The convention for using the regular FFT is:\
ifft(uh_0, uh_1, \'85, uh_\{N-1\}, 2*uh_\{N\}, uh_\{-N-1\}, \'85, uh_\{-1\})\
- Again, notice the factor of 2 for uh_\{N\} and this mode should be real for the physical signal to be real. I have verified that using the regular FFT to perform a real FFT (thereby doubling the length of the vector) is less efficient than the real FFT, as would be expected.\
-\'a0All questions I ever had about the nuances of FFT are addressed in the test codes. So if I ever get confused again, I can look there.\
\
\'95 In addition, I experienced some with the different methods in plan_irfft by setting flags = FFTW.ESTIMATE, FFTW.MEASURE, or FFTW.PATIENT. I did not see any significant advantage to any of these methods. They all look about the same as far as computational time and there is a lot of random variation from test to test. Thus, I am sticking with FFTW.ESTIMATE since it is the default.\
